# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: developmental-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A specialized type of differentiation, known as terminal differentiation, is of importance in some tissues, including vertebrate nervous system, striated muscle, epidermis and gut.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] During terminal differentiation, a precursor cell formerly capable of cell division permanently leaves the cell cycle, dismantles the cell cycle machinery and often expresses a range of genes characteristic of the cell's final function (e.g. myosin and actin for a muscle cell).
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Differentiation may continue to occur after terminal differentiation if the capacity and functions of the cell undergo further changes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Among dividing cells, there are multiple levels of cell potency, which is the cell's ability to differentiate into other cell types.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A greater potency indicates a larger number of cell types that can be derived.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A cell that can differentiate into all cell types, including the placental tissue, is known as *totipotent*.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In mammals, only the zygote and subsequent blastomeres are totipotent, while in plants, many differentiated cells can become totipotent with simple laboratory techniques.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A cell that can differentiate into all cell types of the adult organism is known as *pluripotent*.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Such cells are called meristematic cells in higher plants and embryonic stem cells in animals, though some groups report the presence of adult pluripotent cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Virally induced expression of four transcription factors Oct4, Sox2, c-Myc, and Klf4 (Yamanaka factors) is sufficient to create pluripotent (iPS) cells from adult fibroblasts.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A multipotent cell is one that can differentiate into multiple different, but closely related cell types.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Oligopotent cells are more restricted than multipotent, but can still differentiate into a few closely related cell types.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Finally, unipotent cells can differentiate into only one cell type, but are capable of self-renewal.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In cytopathology, the level of cellular differentiation is used as a measure of cancer progression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] "Grade" is a marker of how differentiated a cell in a tumor is.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Three basic categories of cells make up the mammalian body: germ cells, somatic cells, and stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Each of the approximately 37.2 trillion (3.72×1013) cells in an adult human has its own copy or copies of the genome except certain cell types, such as red blood cells, that lack nuclei in their fully differentiated state.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Most cells are diploid; they have two copies of each chromosome.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Such cells, called somatic cells, make up most of the human body, such as skin and muscle cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cells differentiate to specialize for different functions.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Germ line cells are any line of cells that give rise to gametes—eggs and sperm—and thus are continuous through the generations.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Stem cells, on the other hand, have the ability to divide for indefinite periods and to give rise to specialized cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] They are best described in the context of normal human development.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Development begins when a sperm fertilizes an egg and creates a single cell that has the potential to form an entire organism.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In the first hours after fertilization, this cell divides into identical cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In humans, approximately four days after fertilization and after several cycles of cell division, these cells begin to specialize, forming a hollow sphere of cells, called a blastocyst.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The blastocyst has an outer layer of cells, and inside this hollow sphere, there is a cluster of cells called the inner cell mass.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The cells of the inner cell mass go on to form virtually all of the tissues of the human body.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Although the cells of the inner cell mass can form virtually every type of cell found in the human body, they cannot form an organism.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] These cells are referred to as pluripotent.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Pluripotent stem cells undergo further specialization into multipotent progenitor cells that then give rise to functional cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The ectoderm ends up forming the skin and the nervous system, the mesoderm forms the bones and muscular tissue, and the endoderm forms the internal organ tissues.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Dedifferentiation, or integration, is a cellular process seen in the more basal life forms in animals, such as worms and amphibians where a differentiated cell reverts to an earlier developmental stage—usually as part of a regenerative process.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Dedifferentiation also occurs in plant cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] And, in cell culture in the laboratory, cells can change shape or may lose specific properties such as protein expression—which processes are also termed dedifferentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Some hypothesize that dedifferentiation is an aberration that likely results in cancers, but others explain it as a natural part of the immune response that was lost to humans at some point of evolution.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The molecule reversine, a purine analog, has proven to induce dedifferentiation in myotubes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] These manifestly dedifferentiated cells—now performing essentially as stem cells—could then redifferentiate into osteoblasts and adipocytes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Each specialized cell type in an organism expresses a subset of all the genes that constitute the genome of that species.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Each cell type is defined by its particular pattern of regulated gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cell differentiation is thus a transition of a cell from one cell type to another and it involves a switch from one pattern of gene expression to another.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cellular differentiation during development can be understood as the result of a gene regulatory network.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A regulatory gene and its cis-regulatory modules are nodes in a gene regulatory network; they receive input and create output elsewhere in the network.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The systems biology approach to developmental biology emphasizes the importance of investigating how developmental mechanisms interact to produce predictable patterns (morphogenesis).
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] However, recent research suggests there may be an alternative view.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Based on stochastic gene expression, cellular differentiation is the result of a Darwinian selective process occurring among cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In this frame, protein and gene networks are the result of cellular processes and not their cause.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cellular differentiation is often controlled by cell signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Many of the signal molecules that convey information from cell to cell during the control of cellular differentiation are called growth factors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Although the details of specific signal transduction pathways vary, these pathways often share the following general steps.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A ligand produced by one cell binds to a receptor in the extracellular region of another cell, inducing a conformational change in the receptor.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The shape of the cytoplasmic domain of the receptor changes, and the receptor acquires enzymatic activity.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The receptor then catalyzes reactions that phosphorylate other proteins, activating them.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A cascade of phosphorylation reactions eventually activates a dormant transcription factor or cytoskeletal protein, thus contributing to the differentiation process in the target cell.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cells and tissues can vary in competence, their ability to respond to external signals.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Signal induction refers to cascades of signaling events, during which a cell or tissue signals to another cell or tissue to influence its developmental fate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Yamamoto and Jeffery investigated the role of the lens in eye formation in cave- and surface-dwelling fish, a striking example of induction.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Through reciprocal transplants, Yamamoto and Jeffery found that the lens vesicle of surface fish can induce other parts of the eye to develop in cave- and surface-dwelling fish, while the lens vesicle of the cave-dwelling fish cannot.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Other important mechanisms fall under the category of asymmetric cell divisions, divisions that give rise to daughter cells with distinct developmental fates.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Asymmetric cell divisions can occur because of asymmetrically expressed maternal **cytoplasmic determinants** or because of signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In the former mechanism, distinct daughter cells are created during cytokinesis because of an uneven distribution of regulatory molecules in the parent cell; the distinct cytoplasm that each daughter cell inherits results in a distinct pattern of differentiation for each daughter cell.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A well-studied example of pattern formation by asymmetric divisions is body axis patterning in Drosophila.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] RNA molecules are an important type of intracellular differentiation control signal.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The molecular and genetic basis of asymmetric cell divisions has also been studied in green algae of the genus *Volvox*, a model system for studying how unicellular organisms can evolve into multicellular organisms.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In *Volvox carteri*, the 16 cells in the anterior hemisphere of a 32-cell embryo divide asymmetrically, each producing one large and one small daughter cell.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The size of the cell at the end of all cell divisions determines whether it becomes a specialized germ or somatic cell.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] While evolutionarily conserved molecular processes are involved in the cellular mechanisms underlying these switches, in animal species these are very different from the well-characterized gene regulatory mechanisms of bacteria, and even from those of the animals' closest unicellular relatives.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Specifically, cell differentiation in animals is highly dependent on biomolecular condensates of regulatory proteins and enhancer DNA sequences.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Since each cell, regardless of cell type, possesses the same genome, determination of cell type must occur at the level of gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] While the regulation of gene expression can occur through cis- and trans-regulatory elements including a gene's promoter and enhancers, the problem arises as to how this expression pattern is maintained over numerous generations of cell division.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] As it turns out, epigenetic processes play a crucial role in regulating the decision to adopt a stem, progenitor, or mature cell fate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] This section will focus primarily on mammalian stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In systems biology and mathematical modeling of gene regulatory networks, cell-fate determination is predicted to exhibit certain dynamics, such as attractor-convergence (the attractor can be an equilibrium point, limit cycle or strange attractor) or oscillatory.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The first question that can be asked is the extent and complexity of the role of epigenetic processes in the determination of cell fate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A clear answer to this question can be seen in the 2011 paper by Lister R, *et al.* on aberrant epigenomic programming in human induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] As induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) are thought to mimic embryonic stem cells in their pluripotent properties, few epigenetic differences should exist between them.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] To test this prediction, the authors conducted whole-genome profiling of DNA methylation patterns in several human embryonic stem cell (ESC), iPSC, and progenitor cell lines.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Female adipose cells, lung fibroblasts, and foreskin fibroblasts were reprogrammed into induced pluripotent state with the OCT4, SOX2, KLF4, and MYC genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Patterns of DNA methylation in ESCs, iPSCs, somatic cells were compared.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Lister R, *et al.* observed significant resemblance in methylation levels between embryonic and induced pluripotent cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Around 80% of CG dinucleotides in ESCs and iPSCs were methylated, the same was true of only 60% of CG dinucleotides in somatic cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In addition, somatic cells possessed minimal levels of cytosine methylation in non-CG dinucleotides, while induced pluripotent cells possessed similar levels of methylation as embryonic stem cells, between 0.5 and 1.5%.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Thus, consistent with their respective transcriptional activities, DNA methylation patterns, at least on the genomic level, are similar between ESCs and iPSCs.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] However, upon examining methylation patterns more closely, the authors discovered 1175 regions of differential CG dinucleotide methylation between at least one ES or iPS cell line.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In vitro-induced differentiation of iPSC lines saw transmission of 88% and 46% of hyper and hypo-methylated differentially methylated regions, respectively.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Two conclusions are readily apparent from this study.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] First, epigenetic processes are heavily involved in cell fate determination, as seen from the similar levels of cytosine methylation between induced pluripotent and embryonic stem cells, consistent with their respective patterns of transcription.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Second, the mechanisms of reprogramming (and by extension, differentiation) are very complex and cannot be easily duplicated, as seen by the significant number of differentially methylated regions between ES and iPS cell lines.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Now that these two points have been established, we can examine some of the epigenetic mechanisms that are thought to regulate cellular differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Three transcription factors, OCT4, SOX2, and NANOG – the first two of which are used in induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) reprogramming, along with Klf4 and c-Myc – are highly expressed in undifferentiated embryonic stem cells and are necessary for the maintenance of their pluripotency.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] It is thought that they achieve this through alterations in chromatin structure, such as histone modification and DNA methylation, to restrict or permit the transcription of target genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] While highly expressed, their levels require a precise balance to maintain pluripotency, perturbation of which will promote differentiation towards different lineages based on how the gene expression levels change.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Differential regulation of Oct-4 and SOX2 levels have been shown to precede germ layer fate selection.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Increased levels of Oct4 and decreased levels of Sox2 promote a mesendodermal fate, with Oct4 actively suppressing genes associated with a neural ectodermal fate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Similarly, increased levels of Sox2 and decreased levels of Oct4 promote differentiation towards a neural ectodermal fate, with Sox2 inhibiting differentiation towards a mesendodermal fate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Regardless of the lineage cells differentiate down, suppression of NANOG has been identified as a necessary prerequisite for differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In the realm of gene silencing, Polycomb repressive complex 2, one of two classes of the Polycomb group (PcG) family of proteins, catalyzes the di- and tri-methylation of histone H3 lysine 27 (H3K27me2/me3).
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] By binding to the H3K27me2/3-tagged nucleosome, PRC1 (also a complex of PcG family proteins) catalyzes the mono-ubiquitinylation of histone H2A at lysine 119 (H2AK119Ub1), blocking RNA polymerase II activity and resulting in transcriptional suppression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] PcG knockout ES cells do not differentiate efficiently into the three germ layers, and deletion of the PRC1 and PRC2 genes leads to increased expression of lineage-affiliated genes and unscheduled differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Presumably, PcG complexes are responsible for transcriptionally repressing differentiation and development-promoting genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Alternately, upon receiving differentiation signals, PcG proteins are recruited to promoters of pluripotency transcription factors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] PcG-deficient ES cells can begin differentiation but cannot maintain the differentiated phenotype.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Simultaneously, differentiation and development-promoting genes are activated by Trithorax group (TrxG) chromatin regulators and lose their repression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] TrxG proteins are recruited at regions of high transcriptional activity, where they catalyze the trimethylation of histone H3 lysine 4 (H3K4me3) and promote gene activation through histone acetylation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] PcG and TrxG complexes engage in direct competition and are thought to be functionally antagonistic, creating at differentiation and development-promoting loci what is termed a "bivalent domain" and rendering these genes sensitive to rapid induction or repression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Regulation of gene expression is further achieved through DNA methylation, in which the DNA methyltransferase-mediated methylation of cytosine residues in CpG dinucleotides maintains heritable repression by controlling DNA accessibility.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The majority of CpG sites in embryonic stem cells are unmethylated and appear to be associated with H3K4me3-carrying nucleosomes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Upon differentiation, a small number of genes, including OCT4 and NANOG, are methylated and their promoters repressed to prevent their further expression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Consistently, DNA methylation-deficient embryonic stem cells rapidly enter apoptosis upon in vitro differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] While the DNA sequence of most cells of an organism is the same, the binding patterns of transcription factors and the corresponding gene expression patterns are different.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] To a large extent, differences in transcription factor binding are determined by the chromatin accessibility of their binding sites through histone modification and/or pioneer factors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In particular, it is important to know whether a nucleosome is covering a given genomic binding site or not.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] This can be determined using a chromatin immunoprecipitation assay.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] DNA-nucleosome interactions are characterized by two states: either tightly bound by nucleosomes and transcriptionally inactive, called heterochromatin, or loosely bound and usually, but not always, transcriptionally active, called euchromatin.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The epigenetic processes of histone methylation and acetylation, and their inverses demethylation and deacetylation primarily account for these changes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The effects of acetylation and deacetylation are more predictable.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] An acetyl group is either added to or removed from the positively charged Lysine residues in histones by enzymes called histone acetyltransferases or histone deactylases, respectively.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The acetyl group prevents Lysine's association with the negatively charged DNA backbone.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Methylation is not as straightforward, as neither methylation nor demethylation consistently correlate with either gene activation or repression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] However, certain methylations have been repeatedly shown to either activate or repress genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The trimethylation of lysine 4 on histone 3 (H3K4Me3) is associated with gene activation, whereas trimethylation of lysine 27 on histone 3 represses genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] During differentiation, stem cells change their gene expression profiles.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Recent studies have implicated a role for nucleosome positioning and histone modifications during this process.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] There are two components of this process: turning off the expression of embryonic stem cell (ESC) genes, and the activation of cell fate genes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Lysine specific demethylase 1 (KDM1A) is thought to prevent the use of enhancer regions of pluripotency genes, thereby inhibiting their transcription.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] It interacts with Mi-2/NuRD complex (nucleosome remodelling and histone deacetylase) complex, giving an instance where methylation and acetylation are not discrete and mutually exclusive, but intertwined processes.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A final question to ask concerns the role of cell signaling in influencing the epigenetic processes governing differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Such a role should exist, as it would be reasonable to think that extrinsic signaling can lead to epigenetic remodeling, just as it can lead to changes in gene expression through the activation or repression of different transcription factors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Little direct data is available concerning the specific signals that influence the epigenome, and the majority of current knowledge about the subject consists of speculations on plausible candidate regulators of epigenetic remodeling.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] We will first discuss several major candidates thought to be involved in the induction and maintenance of both embryonic stem cells and their differentiated progeny, and then turn to one example of specific signaling pathways in which more direct evidence exists for its role in epigenetic change.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The first major candidate is Wnt signaling pathway.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The Wnt pathway is involved in all stages of differentiation, and the ligand Wnt3a can substitute for the overexpression of c-Myc in the generation of induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] On the other hand, disruption of β-catenin, a component of the Wnt signaling pathway, leads to decreased proliferation of neural progenitors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Growth factors comprise the second major set of candidates of epigenetic regulators of cellular differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] These morphogens are crucial for development, and include bone morphogenetic proteins, transforming growth factors (TGFs), and fibroblast growth factors (FGFs).
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] TGFs and FGFs have been shown to sustain expression of OCT4, SOX2, and NANOG by downstream signaling to Smad proteins.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Depletion of growth factors promotes the differentiation of ESCs, while genes with bivalent chromatin can become either more restrictive or permissive in their transcription.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Several other signaling pathways are also considered to be primary candidates.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Cytokine leukemia inhibitory factors are associated with the maintenance of mouse ESCs in an undifferentiated state.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] This is achieved through its activation of the Jak-STAT3 pathway, which has been shown to be necessary and sufficient towards maintaining mouse ESC pluripotency.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Retinoic acid can induce differentiation of human and mouse ESCs, and Notch signaling is involved in the proliferation and self-renewal of stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Finally, Sonic hedgehog, in addition to its role as a morphogen, promotes embryonic stem cell differentiation and the self-renewal of somatic stem cells.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The problem, of course, is that the candidacy of these signaling pathways was inferred primarily on the basis of their role in development and cellular differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] While epigenetic regulation is necessary for driving cellular differentiation, they are certainly not sufficient for this process.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Direct modulation of gene expression through modification of transcription factors plays a key role that must be distinguished from heritable epigenetic changes that can persist even in the absence of the original environmental signals.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Only a few examples of signaling pathways leading to epigenetic changes that alter cell fate currently exist, and we will focus on one of them.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Expression of Shh (Sonic hedgehog) upregulates the production of BMI1, a component of the PcG complex that recognizes H3K27me3.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] This occurs in a Gli-dependent manner, as Gli1 and Gli2 are downstream effectors of the Hedgehog signaling pathway.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In culture, Bmi1 mediates the Hedgehog pathway's ability to promote human mammary stem cell self-renewal.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In both humans and mice, researchers showed Bmi1 to be highly expressed in proliferating immature cerebellar granule cell precursors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] When Bmi1 was knocked out in mice, impaired cerebellar development resulted, leading to significant reductions in postnatal brain mass along with abnormalities in motor control and behavior.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] A separate study showed a significant decrease in neural stem cell proliferation along with increased astrocyte proliferation in Bmi null mice.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] An alternative model of cellular differentiation during embryogenesis is that positional information is based on mechanical signalling by the cytoskeleton using Embryonic differentiation waves.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The mechanical signal is then epigenetically transduced via signal transduction systems (of which specific molecules such as Wnt are part) to result in differential gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In summary, the role of signaling in the epigenetic control of cell fate in mammals is largely unknown, but distinct examples exist that indicate the likely existence of further such mechanisms.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] In order to fulfill the purpose of regenerating a variety of tissues, adult stems are known to migrate from their niches, adhere to new extracellular matrices (ECM) and differentiate.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The ductility of these microenvironments are unique to different tissue types.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The ECM surrounding brain, muscle and bone tissues range from soft to stiff.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The transduction of the stem cells into these cells types is not directed solely by chemokine cues and cell to cell signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The elasticity of the microenvironment can also affect the differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs which originate in bone marrow.) When MSCs are placed on substrates of the same stiffness as brain, muscle and bone ECM, the MSCs take on properties of those respective cell types.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Matrix sensing requires the cell to pull against the matrix at focal adhesions, which triggers a cellular mechano-transducer to generate a signal to be informed what force is needed to deform the matrix.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] To determine the key players in matrix-elasticity-driven lineage specification in MSCs, different matrix microenvironments were mimicked.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] From these experiments, it was concluded that focal adhesions of the MSCs were the cellular mechano-transducer sensing the differences of the matrix elasticity.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The non-muscle myosin IIa-c isoforms generates the forces in the cell that lead to signaling of early commitment markers.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Nonmuscle myosin IIa generates the least force increasing to non-muscle myosin IIc.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] There are also factors in the cell that inhibit non-muscle myosin II, such as blebbistatin.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] This makes the cell effectively blind to the surrounding matrix.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] Researchers have achieved some success in inducing stem cell-like properties in HEK 239 cells by providing a soft matrix without the use of diffusing factors.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The stem-cell properties appear to be linked to tension in the cells' actin network.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] One identified mechanism for matrix-induced differentiation is tension-induced proteins, which remodel chromatin in response to mechanical stretch.
[src:developmental-biology/cell-differentiation] The RhoA pathway is also implicated in this process.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The main processes involved in the embryonic development of animals are: tissue patterning (via regional specification and patterned cell differentiation); tissue growth; and tissue morphogenesis.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The development of plants involves similar processes to that of animals.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] However, plant cells are mostly immotile so morphogenesis is achieved by differential growth, without cell movements.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Also, the inductive signals and the genes involved are different from those that control animal development.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Cell differentiation is the process whereby different functional cell types arise in development.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] For example, neurons, muscle fibers and hepatocytes (liver cells) are well known types of differentiated cells.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Differentiated cells usually produce large amounts of a few proteins that are required for their specific function and this gives them the characteristic appearance that enables them to be recognized under the light microscope.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The genes encoding these proteins are highly active.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Typically their chromatin structure is very open, allowing access for the transcription enzymes, and specific transcription factors bind to regulatory sequences in the DNA in order to activate gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] For example, NeuroD is a key transcription factor for neuronal differentiation, myogenin for muscle differentiation, and HNF4 for hepatocyte differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Cell differentiation is usually the final stage of development, preceded by several states of commitment which are not visibly differentiated.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] A single tissue, formed from a single type of progenitor cell or stem cell, often consists of several differentiated cell types.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Control of their formation involves a process of lateral inhibition, based on the properties of the Notch signaling pathway.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] For example, in the neural plate of the embryo this system operates to generate a population of neuronal precursor cells in which NeuroD is highly expressed.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Regeneration indicates the ability to regrow a missing part.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This is very prevalent amongst plants, which show continuous growth, and also among colonial animals such as hydroids and ascidians.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] But most interest by developmental biologists has been shown in the regeneration of parts in free living animals.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In particular four models have been the subject of much investigation.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Two of these have the ability to regenerate whole bodies: *Hydra*, which can regenerate any part of the polyp from a small fragment, and planarian worms, which can usually regenerate both heads and tails.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Both of these examples have continuous cell turnover fed by stem cells and, at least in planaria, at least some of the stem cells have been shown to be pluripotent.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The other two models show only distal regeneration of appendages.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] These are the insect appendages, usually the legs of hemimetabolous insects such as the cricket, and the limbs of urodele amphibians.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Considerable information is now available about amphibian limb regeneration and it is known that each cell type regenerates itself, except for connective tissues where there is considerable interconversion between cartilage, dermis and tendons.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In terms of the pattern of structures, this is controlled by a re-activation of signals active in the embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] There is still debate about the old question of whether regeneration is a "pristine" or an "adaptive" property.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] If the former is the case, with improved knowledge, we might expect to be able to improve regenerative ability in humans.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] If the latter, then each instance of regeneration is presumed to have arisen by natural selection in circumstances particular to the species, so no general rules would be expected.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The sperm and egg fuse in the process of fertilization to form a fertilized egg, or zygote.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This undergoes a period of divisions to form a ball or sheet of similar cells called a blastula or blastoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] These cell divisions are usually rapid with no growth so the daughter cells are half the size of the mother cell and the whole embryo stays about the same size.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Mouse epiblast primordial germ cells (see Figure: "The initial stages of human embryogenesis") undergo extensive epigenetic reprogramming.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This process involves genome-wide DNA demethylation, chromatin reorganization and epigenetic imprint erasure leading to totipotency.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] DNA demethylation is carried out by a process that utilizes the DNA base excision repair pathway.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Morphogenetic movements convert the cell mass into a three layered structure consisting of multicellular sheets called ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] During cleavage and gastrulation the first regional specification events occur.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In addition to the formation of the three germ layers themselves, these often generate extraembryonic structures, such as the mammalian placenta, needed for support and nutrition of the embryo, and also establish differences of commitment along the anteroposterior axis (head, trunk and tail).
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Regional specification is initiated by the presence of cytoplasmic determinants in one part of the zygote.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The cells that contain the determinant become a signaling center and emit an inducing factor.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Because the inducing factor is produced in one place, diffuses away, and decays, it forms a concentration gradient, high near the source cells and low further away.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The remaining cells of the embryo, which do not contain the determinant, are competent to respond to different concentrations by upregulating specific developmental control genes.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This results in a series of zones becoming set up, arranged at progressively greater distance from the signaling center.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In each zone a different combination of developmental control genes is upregulated.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] These genes encode transcription factors which upregulate new combinations of gene activity in each region.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Among other functions, these transcription factors control expression of genes conferring specific adhesive and motility properties on the cells in which they are active.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Because of these different morphogenetic properties, the cells of each germ layer move to form sheets such that the ectoderm ends up on the outside, mesoderm in the middle, and endoderm on the inside.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Morphogenetic movements not only change the shape and structure of the embryo, but by bringing cell sheets into new spatial relationships they also make possible new phases of signaling and response between them.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In addition, first morphogenetic movements of embryogenesis, such as gastrulation, epiboly and twisting, directly activate pathways involved in endomesoderm specification through mechanotransduction processes.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This property was suggested to be evolutionary inherited from endomesoderm specification as mechanically stimulated by marine environmental hydrodynamic flow in first animal organisms (first metazoa).
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] For each territory of cells the growth rate is controlled by the combination of genes that are active.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Free-living embryos do not grow in mass as they have no external food supply.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] But embryos fed by a placenta or extraembryonic yolk supply can grow very fast, and changes to relative growth rate between parts in these organisms help to produce the final overall anatomy.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The whole process needs to be coordinated in time and how this is controlled is not understood.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] There may be a master clock able to communicate with all parts of the embryo that controls the course of events, or timing may depend simply on local causal sequences of events.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Developmental processes are very evident during the process of metamorphosis.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This occurs in various types of animal such as insects, amphibians, some fish, and many marine invertebrates.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Well-known examples are seen in frogs, which usually hatch as a tadpole and metamorphoses to an adult frog, and certain insects which hatch as a larva and then become remodeled to the adult form during a pupal stage.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] All the developmental processes listed above occur during metamorphosis.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Examples that have been especially well studied include tail loss and other changes in the tadpole of the frog *Xenopus*, and the biology of the imaginal discs, which generate the adult body parts of the fly *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Plant **development** is the process by which structures originate and mature as a plant grows.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] It is studied in plant anatomy and plant physiology as well as plant morphology.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Plants constantly produce new tissues and structures throughout their life from meristems located at the tips of organs, or between mature tissues.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Thus, a living plant always has embryonic tissues.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] By contrast, an animal embryo will very early produce all of the body parts that it will ever have in its life.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] When the animal is born (or hatches from its egg), it has all its body parts and from that point will only grow larger and more mature.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The properties of organization seen in a plant are emergent properties which are more than the sum of the individual parts.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] A vascular plant begins from a single celled zygote, formed by fertilisation of an egg cell by a sperm cell.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] From that point, it begins to divide to form a plant embryo through the process of embryogenesis.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] As this happens, the resulting cells will organize so that one end becomes the first root, while the other end forms the tip of the shoot.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In seed plants, the embryo will develop one or more "seed leaves" (cotyledons).
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] By the end of embryogenesis, the young plant will have all the parts necessary to begin its life.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Once the embryo germinates from its seed or parent plant, it begins to produce additional organs (leaves, stems, and roots) through the process of organogenesis.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] New roots grow from root meristems located at the tip of the root, and new stems and leaves grow from shoot meristems located at the tip of the shoot.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Branching occurs when small clumps of cells left behind by the meristem, and which have not yet undergone cellular differentiation to form a specialized tissue, begin to grow as the tip of a new root or shoot.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Growth from any such meristem at the tip of a root or shoot is termed primary growth and results in the lengthening of that root or shoot.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Secondary growth results in widening of a root or shoot from divisions of cells in a cambium.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In addition to growth by cell division, a plant may grow through **cell elongation**.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This occurs when individual cells or groups of cells grow longer.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Not all plant cells will grow to the same length.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] When cells on one side of a stem grow longer and faster than cells on the other side, the stem will bend to the side of the slower growing cells as a result.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This directional growth can occur via a plant's response to a particular stimulus, such as light (phototropism), gravity (gravitropism), water, (hydrotropism), and physical contact (thigmotropism).
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Plant growth and development are mediated by specific plant hormones and plant growth regulators (PGRs) (Ross et al.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Endogenous hormone levels are influenced by plant age, cold hardiness, dormancy, and other metabolic conditions; photoperiod, drought, temperature, and other external environmental conditions; and exogenous sources of PGRs, e.g., externally applied and of rhizospheric origin.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Plants exhibit natural variation in their form and structure.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] While all organisms vary from individual to individual, plants exhibit an additional type of variation.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Within a single individual, parts are repeated which may differ in form and structure from other similar parts.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] This variation is most easily seen in the leaves of a plant, though other organs such as stems and flowers may show similar variation.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] There are three primary causes of this variation: positional effects, environmental effects, and juvenility.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Transcription factors and transcriptional regulatory networks play key roles in plant morphogenesis and their evolution.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] During plant landing, many novel transcription factor families emerged and are preferentially wired into the networks of multicellular development, reproduction, and organ development, contributing to more complex morphogenesis of land plants.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Most land plants share a common ancestor, multicellular algae.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] An example of the evolution of plant morphology is seen in charophytes.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Studies have shown that charophytes have traits that are homologous to land plants.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] There are two main theories of the evolution of plant morphology, these theories are the homologous theory and the antithetic theory.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The commonly accepted theory for the evolution of plant morphology is the antithetic theory.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The antithetic theory states that the multiple mitotic divisions that take place before meiosis, cause the development of the sporophyte.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Then the sporophyte will development as an independent organism.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Much of developmental biology research in recent decades has focused on the use of a small number of model organisms.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] It has turned out that there is much conservation of developmental mechanisms across the animal kingdom.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In early development different vertebrate species all use essentially the same inductive signals and the same genes encoding regional identity.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Even invertebrates use a similar repertoire of signals and genes although the body parts formed are significantly different.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Model organisms each have some particular experimental advantages which have enabled them to become popular among researchers.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] In one sense they are "models" for the whole animal kingdom, and in another sense they are "models" for human development, which is difficult to study directly for both ethical and practical reasons.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Model organisms have been most useful for elucidating the broad nature of developmental mechanisms.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] The more detail is sought, the more they differ from each other and from humans.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Also popular for some purposes have been sea urchins and ascidians.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] For studies of regeneration urodele amphibians such as the axolotl *Ambystoma mexicanum* are used, and also planarian worms such as *Schmidtea mediterranea*.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Organoids have also been demonstrated as an efficient model for development.
[src:developmental-biology/developmental-biology] Plant development has focused on the thale cress *Arabidopsis thaliana* as a model organism.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In developmental biology, **animal embryonic development**, also known as **animal embryogenesis**, is the developmental stage of an animal embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Embryonic development starts with the fertilization of an egg cell (ovum) by a sperm cell (spermatozoon).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Once fertilized, the ovum becomes a single diploid cell known as a zygote.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The zygote undergoes mitotic divisions with no significant growth (a process known as cleavage) and cellular differentiation, leading to development of a multicellular embryo after passing through an organizational checkpoint during mid-embryogenesis.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In mammals, the term refers chiefly to the early stages of prenatal development, whereas the terms fetus and fetal development describe later stages.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The embryo then transforms into the next stage of development, the nature of which varies among different animal species (examples of possible next stages include a fetus and a larva).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The egg cell is generally asymmetric, having an animal pole (future ectoderm).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] It is covered with protective envelopes, with different layers.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The first envelope – the one in contact with the membrane of the egg – is made of glycoproteins and is known as the vitelline membrane (zona pellucida in mammals).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Different taxa show different cellular and acellular envelopes englobing the vitelline membrane.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Fertilization is the fusion of gametes to produce a new organism.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In animals, the process involves a sperm fusing with an ovum, which eventually leads to the development of an embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Depending on the animal species, the process can occur within the body of the female in internal fertilization, or outside in the case of external fertilization.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The fertilized egg cell is known as the zygote.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] To prevent more than one sperm fertilizing the egg (polyspermy), fast block and slow block to polyspermy are used.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Fast block, the membrane potential rapidly depolarizing and then returning to normal, happens immediately after an egg is fertilized by a single sperm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Cell division with no significant growth, producing a cluster of cells that is the same size as the original zygote, is called cleavage.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] At least four initial cell divisions occur, resulting in a dense ball of at least sixteen cells called the morula.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In the early mouse embryo, the sister cells of each division remain connected during interphase by microtubule bridges.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The different cells derived from cleavage, up to the blastula stage, are called blastomeres.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Depending mostly on the amount of yolk in the egg, the cleavage can be holoblastic (total) or meroblastic (partial).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Holoblastic cleavage occurs in animals with little yolk in their eggs, such as humans and other mammals who receive nourishment as embryos from the mother, via the placenta or milk, such as might be secreted from a marsupium.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Meroblastic cleavage occurs in animals whose eggs have more yolk (i.e. birds and reptiles).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Because cleavage is impeded in the vegetal pole, there is an uneven distribution and size of cells, being more numerous and smaller at the animal pole of the zygote.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In holoblastic eggs, the first cleavage always occurs along the vegetal-animal axis of the egg, and the second cleavage is perpendicular to the first.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The end of cleavage is known as midblastula transition and coincides with the onset of zygotic transcription.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In amniotes, the cells of the morula are at first closely aggregated, but soon they become arranged into an outer or peripheral layer, the trophoblast, which does not contribute to the formation of the embryo proper, and an inner cell mass, from which the embryo is developed.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Fluid collects between the trophoblast and the greater part of the inner cell-mass, and thus the morula is converted into a vesicle, called the blastodermic vesicle.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The inner cell mass remains in contact, however, with the trophoblast at one pole of the ovum; this is named the embryonic pole, since it indicates the location where the future embryo will develop.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] After the seventh cleavage has produced 128 cells, the morula becomes a blastula.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The blastula is usually a spherical layer of cells (the blastoderm) surrounding a fluid-filled or yolk-filled cavity the blastocoel.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Mammals at this stage form a structure called the blastocyst,[1] characterized by an inner cell mass that is distinct from the surrounding blastula.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The blastocyst is similar in structure to the blastula but their cells have different fates.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In the mouse, primordial germ cells arise from the inner cell mass (the epiblast) as a result of extensive genome-wide reprogramming.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Reprogramming involves global DNA demethylation facilitated by the DNA base excision repair pathway as well as chromatin reorganization, and results in cellular totipotency.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] As already stated, the cells of the trophoblast do not contribute to the formation of the embryo proper; they form the ectoderm of the chorion and play an important part in the development of the placenta.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] On the deep surface of the inner cell mass, a layer of flattened cells, called the endoderm, is differentiated and quickly assumes the form of a small sac, called the yolk sac.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Spaces appear between the remaining cells of the mass and, by the enlargement and coalescence of these spaces, a cavity called the amniotic cavity is gradually developed.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The floor of this cavity is formed by the embryonic disk, which is composed of a layer of prismatic cells – the embryonic ectoderm, derived from the inner cell mass and lying in apposition with the endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The embryonic disc becomes oval and then pear-shaped, the wider end being directed forward.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Towards the narrow, posterior end, an opaque area, the primitive streak, is formed and extends along the middle of the disc for about half of its length; at the anterior end of the streak there is a knob-like thickening termed the primitive node or knot, (known as *Hensen's knot* in birds).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] A shallow groove, the primitive groove, appears on the surface of the streak, and the anterior end of this groove communicates by means of an aperture, the blastopore, with the yolk sac.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The primitive streak is produced by a thickening of the axial part of the ectoderm, the cells of which multiply, grow downward, and blend with those of the subjacent endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] From the sides of the primitive streak a third layer of cells, the mesoderm, extends laterally between the ectoderm and endoderm; the caudal end of the primitive streak forms the cloacal membrane.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The blastoderm now consists of three layers, an outer ectoderm, a middle mesoderm, and an inner endoderm; each has distinctive characteristics and gives rise to certain tissues of the body.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] For many mammals, it is sometime during formation of the germ layers that implantation of the embryo in the uterus of the mother occurs.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] During gastrulation cells migrate to the interior of the blastula, subsequently forming two (in diploblastic animals) or three (triploblastic) germ layers.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The embryo during this process is called a gastrula.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The germ layers are referred to as the ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In most animals, a blastopore is formed at the point where cells are migrating inward.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Two major groups of animals can be distinguished according to the blastopore's fate.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In deuterostomes the anus forms from the blastopore, while in protostomes it develops into the mouth.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In front of the primitive streak, two longitudinal ridges, caused by a folding up of the ectoderm, make their appearance, one on either side of the middle line formed by the streak.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] These are named the neural folds; they commence some little distance behind the anterior end of the embryonic disk, where they are continuous with each other, and from there gradually extend backward, one on either side of the anterior end of the primitive streak.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Between these folds is a shallow median groove, the neural groove.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The groove gradually deepens as the neural folds become elevated, and ultimately the folds meet and coalesce in the middle line and convert the groove into a closed tube, the neural tube or canal, the ectodermal wall of which forms the rudiment of the nervous system.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Before the neural groove is closed, a ridge of ectodermal cells appears along the prominent margin of each neural fold; this is termed the neural crest or ganglion ridge, and from it the spinal and cranial nerve ganglia and the ganglia of the sympathetic nervous system are developed.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] By the upward growth of the mesoderm, the neural tube is ultimately separated from the overlying ectoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The cephalic end of the neural groove exhibits several dilatations that, when the tube is closed, assume the form of the three primary brain vesicles, and correspond, respectively, to the future forebrain (prosencephalon), midbrain (mesencephalon), and hindbrain (rhombencephalon) (Fig.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The walls of the vesicles are developed into the nervous tissue and neuroglia of the brain, and their cavities are modified to form its ventricles.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The remainder of the tube forms the spinal cord (medulla spinalis); from its ectodermal wall the nervous and neuroglial elements of the spinal cord are developed, while the cavity persists as the central canal.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The extension of the mesoderm takes place throughout the whole of the embryonic and extra-embryonic areas of the ovum, except in certain regions.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] One of these is seen immediately in front of the neural tube.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Here the mesoderm extends forward in the form of two crescentic masses, which meet in the middle line so as to enclose behind them an area that is devoid of mesoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Over this area, the ectoderm and endoderm come into direct contact with each other and constitute a thin membrane, the buccopharyngeal membrane, which forms a septum between the primitive mouth and pharynx.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In front of the buccopharyngeal area, where the lateral crescents of mesoderm fuse in the middle line, the pericardium is afterward developed, and this region is therefore designated the pericardial area.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] A second region where the mesoderm is absent, at least for a time, is that immediately in front of the pericardial area.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] This is termed the proamniotic area, and is the region where the proamnion is developed; in humans, however, it appears that a proamnion is never formed.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] A third region is at the hind end of the embryo, where the ectoderm and endoderm come into apposition and form the cloacal membrane.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Somitogenesis is the process by which somites (primitive segments) are produced.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] These segmented tissue blocks differentiate into skeletal muscle, vertebrae, and dermis of all vertebrates.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Somitogenesis begins with the formation of somitomeres (whorls of concentric mesoderm) marking the future somites in the presomitic mesoderm (unsegmented paraxial).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The presomitic mesoderm gives rise to successive pairs of somites, identical in appearance that differentiate into the same cell types but the structures formed by the cells vary depending upon the anteroposterior (e.g., the thoracic vertebrae have ribs, the lumbar vertebrae do not).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Somites have unique positional values along this axis and it is thought that these are specified by the Hox homeotic genes.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Each segment contains a central cavity (known as a [myocoel), which, however, is soon filled with angular and spindle-shape cells.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The somites lie immediately under the ectoderm on the lateral aspect of the neural tube and notochord, and are connected to the lateral mesoderm by the intermediate cell mass.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Those of the trunk may be arranged in the following groups, viz.: cervical 8, thoracic 12, lumbar 5, sacral 5, and coccygeal from 5 to 8.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Those of the occipital region of the head are usually described as being four in number.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In mammals, somites of the head can be recognized only in the occipital region, but a study of the lower vertebrates leads to the belief that they are present also in the anterior part of the head and that, altogether, nine segments are represented in the cephalic region.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] At some point after the different germ layers are defined, organogenesis begins.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The first stage in vertebrates is called neurulation, where the neural plate folds forming the neural tube (see above).
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] Other common organs or structures that arise at this time include the heart and somites (also above), but from now on embryogenesis follows no common pattern among the different taxa of the animalia.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] In most animals organogenesis, along with morphogenesis, results in a larva.
[src:developmental-biology/embryonic-development] The hatching of the larva, which must then undergo metamorphosis, marks the end of embryonic development.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In triploblastic organisms, including the human, the gastrula is trilaminar (three-layered).
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] These three germ layers are the ectoderm (outer layer), mesoderm (middle layer), and endoderm (inner layer).
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] These germ layers form as epiblast cells move through the primitive streak, while undergoing epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition and ingression.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This forms the mesoderm and endoderm, while the remaining epiblast cells differentiate into the ectoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In diploblastic organisms, such as Cnidaria and Ctenophora, the gastrula has only ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The two layers are also sometimes referred to as the *hypoblast* and *epiblast*.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Sponges do not go through the gastrula stage.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrulation takes place after cleavage and the formation of the blastula, or blastocyst.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrulation is followed by organogenesis, when individual organs develop within the newly formed germ layers.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Each layer gives rise to specific tissues and organs in the developing embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] These movements drive germ layer formation and contributes to the differentiation of the body plan during gastrulation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The terms "gastrula" and "gastrulation" were coined by Ernst Haeckel, in his 1872 work *"Biology of Calcareous Sponges"*.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrula (literally, "little belly") is a neo-Latin diminutive based on the Ancient Greek γαστήρ **gastḗr** ("a belly").
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrulation is highly variable across the animal kingdom but has underlying similarities.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrulation has been studied in many animals, but some models have been used for longer than others.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Furthermore, it is easier to study development in animals that develop outside the mother.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Model organisms whose gastrulation is understood in the greatest detail include the mollusc, sea urchin, frog, and chicken.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The distinction between protostomes and deuterostomes is based on the direction in which the mouth (stoma) develops in relation to the **blastopore**.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Protostome derives from the Greek word protostoma meaning "first mouth" (πρῶτος + στόμα) whereas Deuterostome's etymology is "second mouth" from the words second and mouth (δεύτερος + στόμα).
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Sea urchins have been important model organisms in developmental biology since the 19th century.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Their gastrulation is often considered the archetype for invertebrate deuterostomes.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Sea urchins exhibit highly stereotyped cleavage patterns and cell fates.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Maternally deposited mRNAs establish the organizing center of the sea urchin embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Canonical Wnt and Delta-Notch signaling progressively segregate progressive endoderm and mesoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The first cells to internalize are the primary mesenchyme cells (PMCs), which have a skeletogenic fate, which ingress during the blastula stage.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Gastrulation – internalization of the prospective endoderm and non-skeletogenic mesoderm – begins shortly thereafter with invagination and other cell rearrangements the vegetal pole, which contribute approximately 30% to the final archenteron length.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The gut's final length depends on cell rearrangements within the archenteron.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The frog genus *Xenopus* has been used as a model organism for the study of gastrulation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The sperm contributes one of the two mitotic asters needed to complete first cleavage.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The sperm can enter anywhere in the animal half of the egg but its exact point of entry will break the egg's radial symmetry by organizing the cytoskeleton.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Prior to first cleavage, the egg's cortex rotates relative to the internal cytoplasm by the coordinated action of microtubules, in a process known as cortical rotation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This displacement brings maternally loaded determinants of cell fate from the equatorial cytoplasm and vegetal cortex into contact, and together these determinants set up the organizer.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Thus, the area on the vegetal side opposite the sperm entry point will become the organizer.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Hilde Mangold, working in the lab of Hans Spemann, demonstrated that this special "organizer" of the embryo is necessary and sufficient to induce gastrulation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The dorsal lip of the blastopore is the mechanical driver of gastrulation, and the first sign of invagination seen in the frog.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Specification of endoderm depends on rearrangement of maternally deposited determinants, leading to nuclearization of Beta-catenin.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Mesoderm is induced by signaling from the presumptive endoderm to cells that would otherwise become ectoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In the frog, *Xenopus,* one of the signals is retinoic acid (RA).
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] RA signaling in this organism can affect the formation of the endoderm and depending on the timing of the signaling, it can determine the fate whether its pancreatic, intestinal, or respiratory.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Other signals such as Wnt and BMP also play a role in respiratory fate of the *Xenopus* by activating cell lineage tracers.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In amniotes (reptiles, birds and mammals), gastrulation involves the creation of the blastopore, an opening into the archenteron.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Note that the blastopore is not an opening into the blastocoel, the space within the blastula, but represents a new inpocketing that pushes the existing surfaces of the blastula together.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In amniotes, gastrulation occurs in the following sequence: (1) the embryo becomes asymmetric; (2) the primitive streak forms; (3) cells from the epiblast at the primitive streak undergo an epithelial to mesenchymal transition and ingress at the primitive streak to form the germ layers.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In preparation for gastrulation, the embryo must become asymmetric along both the proximal-distal axis and the anteroposterior axis.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The proximal-distal axis is formed when the cells of the embryo form the "egg cylinder", which consists of the four membranes of the extraembryonic tissue, which give rise to structures like the placenta, at the proximal end and the epiblast at the distal end.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Many signaling pathways contribute to this reorganization, including BMP, FGF, nodal, and Wnt.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Visceral endoderm surrounds the epiblast.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The distal visceral endoderm (DVE) migrates to the anterior portion of the embryo, forming the anterior visceral endoderm (AVE).
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This breaks anterior-posterior symmetry and is regulated by nodal signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The primitive streak is formed at the beginning of gastrulation and is found at the junction between the extraembryonic tissue and the epiblast on the posterior side of the embryo and the site of ingression.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Formation of the primitive streak is reliant upon nodal signaling in the Koller's sickle within the cells contributing to the primitive streak and BMP4 signaling from the extraembryonic tissue.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Furthermore, Cer1 and Lefty1 restrict the primitive streak to the appropriate location by antagonizing nodal signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The region defined as the primitive streak continues to grow towards the distal tip.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] During the early stages of development, the primitive streak is the structure that will establish bilateral symmetry, determine the site of gastrulation and initiate germ layer formation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] To form the streak, reptiles, birds and mammals arrange mesenchymal cells along the prospective midline, establishing the first embryonic axis, as well as the place where cells will ingress and migrate during the process of gastrulation and germ layer formation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The primitive streak extends through this midline and creates the antero-posterior body axis, becoming the first symmetry-breaking event in the embryo, and marks the beginning of gastrulation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This process involves the ingression of mesoderm and endoderm progenitors and their migration to their ultimate position, where they will differentiate into the three germ layers.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The localization of the cell adhesion and signaling molecule beta-catenin is critical to the proper formation of the organizer region that is responsible for initiating gastrulation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In order for the cells to move from the epithelium of the epiblast through the primitive streak to form a new layer, the cells must undergo an epithelial to mesenchymal transition (EMT) to lose their epithelial characteristics, such as cell–cell adhesion.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] FGF signaling is necessary for proper EMT.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] FGFR1 is needed for the up regulation of SNAI1, which down regulates E-cadherin, causing a loss of cell adhesion.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Following the EMT, the cells ingress through the primitive streak and spread out to form a new layer of cells or join existing layers.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] FGF8 is implicated in the process of this dispersal from the primitive streak.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] During gastrulation, the cells are differentiated into the ectoderm or mesendoderm, which then separates into the mesoderm and endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The endoderm and mesoderm form due to the nodal signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Nodal signaling uses ligands that are part of TGFβ family.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] These ligands will signal transmembrane serine/threonine kinase receptors, and this will then phosphorylate Smad2 and Smad3.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This protein will then attach itself to Smad4 and relocate to the nucleus where the mesendoderm genes will begin to be transcribed.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The Wnt pathway along with β-catenin plays a key role in nodal signaling and endoderm formation.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Fibroblast growth factors (FGF), canonical Wnt pathway, bone morphogenetic protein (BMP), and retinoic acid (RA) are all important in the formation and development of the endoderm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] FGF are important in producing the homeobox gene which regulates early anatomical development.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] BMP signaling plays a role in the liver and promotes hepatic fate.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] RA signaling also induce homeobox genes such as Hoxb1 and Hoxa5.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In mice, if there is a lack in RA signaling the mouse will not develop lungs.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] RA signaling also has multiple uses in organ formation of the pharyngeal arches, the foregut, and hindgut.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] However, it is important to relate the observations in culture to the processes occurring in the embryo for context.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] In *vitro* fertilization occurs in a laboratory.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The process of in *vitro* fertilization is when mature eggs are removed from the ovaries and are placed in a cultured medium where they are fertilized by sperm.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] 14 days after fertilization the primitive streak forms.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The formation of the primitive streak has been known to some countries as "human individuality".
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] This means that the embryo is now a being itself, it is its own entity.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] The countries that believe this have created a 14-day rule in which it is illegal to study or experiment on a human embryo after the 14-day period in *vitro*.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] Research has been conducted on the first 14 days of an embryo, but no known studies have been done after the 14 days.
[src:developmental-biology/gastrulation] With the rule in place, mice embryos are used understand the development after 14 days; however, there are differences in the development between mice and humans.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] A **homeobox** is a DNA sequence, around 180 base pairs long, that regulates large-scale anatomical features in the early stages of embryonic development.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Mutations in a homeobox may change large-scale anatomical features of the full-grown organism.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeoboxes are found within genes that are involved in the regulation of patterns of anatomical development (morphogenesis) in animals, fungi, plants, and numerous single cell eukaryotes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeobox genes encode **homeodomain** protein products that are transcription factors sharing a characteristic protein fold structure that binds DNA to regulate expression of target genes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins regulate gene expression and cell differentiation during early embryonic development, thus mutations in homeobox genes can cause developmental disorders.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeosis is a term coined by William Bateson to describe the outright replacement of a discrete body part with another body part, e.g. antennapedia—replacement of the antenna on the head of a fruit fly with legs.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The "homeo-" prefix in the words "homeobox" and "homeodomain" stems from this mutational phenotype, which is observed when some of these genes are mutated in animals.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The homeobox domain was first identified in a number of *Drosophila* homeotic and segmentation proteins, but is now known to be well-conserved in many other animals, including vertebrates.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The existence of homeobox genes was first discovered in *Drosophila* by isolating the gene responsible for a homeotic transformation where legs grow from the head instead of the expected antennae.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Walter Gehring identified a gene called *antennapedia* that caused this homeotic phenotype.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Analysis of *antennapedia* revealed that this gene contained a 180 base pair sequence that encoded a DNA binding domain, which William McGinnis termed the "homeobox".
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The existence of additional *Drosophila* genes containing the *antennapedia* homeobox sequence was independently reported by Ernst Hafen, Michael Levine, William McGinnis, and Walter Jakob Gehring of the University of Basel in Switzerland and Matthew P.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Scott and Amy Weiner of Indiana University in Bloomington in 1984.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Isolation of homologous genes by Edward de Robertis and William McGinnis revealed that numerous genes from a variety of species contained the homeobox.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Subsequent phylogenetic studies detailing the evolutionary relationship between homeobox-containing genes showed that these genes are present in all bilaterian animals.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The characteristic homeodomain protein fold consists of a 60-amino acid long domain composed of three alpha helices.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Helix 2 and helix 3 form a so-called helix-turn-helix (HTH) structure, where the two alpha helices are connected by a short loop region.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The N-terminal two helices of the homeodomain are antiparallel and the longer C-terminal helix is roughly perpendicular to the axes of the first two.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] It is this third helix that interacts directly with DNA via a number of hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic interactions, as well as indirect interactions via water molecules, which occur between specific side chains and the exposed bases within the major groove of the DNA.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins are found in eukaryotes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Through the HTH motif, they share limited sequence similarity and structural similarity to prokaryotic transcription factors, such as lambda phage proteins that alter the expression of genes in prokaryotes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The HTH motif shows some sequence similarity but a similar structure in a wide range of DNA-binding proteins (e.g., cro and repressor proteins, homeodomain proteins, etc.).
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomains can bind both specifically and nonspecifically to B-DNA with the C-terminal recognition helix aligning in the DNA's major groove and the unstructured peptide "tail" at the N-terminus aligning in the minor groove.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The recognition helix and the inter-helix loops are rich in arginine and lysine residues, which form hydrogen bonds to the DNA backbone.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Conserved hydrophobic residues in the center of the recognition helix aid in stabilizing the helix packing.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins show a preference for the DNA sequence 5'-TAAT-3'; sequence-independent binding occurs with significantly lower affinity.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The specificity of a single homeodomain protein is usually not enough to recognize specific target gene promoters, making cofactor binding an important mechanism for controlling binding sequence specificity and target gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] To achieve higher target specificity, homeodomain proteins form complexes with other transcription factors to recognize the promoter region of a specific target gene.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins function as transcription factors due to the DNA binding properties of the conserved HTH motif.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins are considered to be master control genes, meaning that a single protein can regulate expression of many target genes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Homeodomain proteins direct the formation of the body axes and body structures during early embryonic development.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Many homeodomain proteins induce cellular differentiation by initiating the cascades of coregulated genes required to produce individual tissues and organs.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Other proteins in the family, such as NANOG are involved in maintaining pluripotency and preventing cell differentiation.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Hox genes and their associated microRNAs are highly conserved developmental master regulators with tight tissue-specific, spatiotemporal control.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] These genes are known to be dysregulated in several cancers and are often controlled by DNA methylation.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The regulation of Hox genes is highly complex and involves reciprocal interactions, mostly inhibitory.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Drosophila is known to use the polycomb and trithorax complexes to maintain the expression of Hox genes after the down-regulation of the pair-rule and gap genes that occurs during larval development.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Polycomb-group proteins can silence the Hox genes by modulation of chromatin structure.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Mutations to homeobox genes can produce easily visible phenotypic changes in body segment identity, such as the Antennapedia and Bithorax mutant phenotypes in *Drosophila*.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Duplication of homeobox genes can produce new body segments, and such duplications are likely to have been important in the evolution of segmented animals.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Phylogenetic analysis of homeobox gene sequences and homeodomain protein structures suggests that the last common ancestor of plants, fungi, and animals had at least two homeobox genes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Molecular evidence shows that some limited number of Hox genes have existed in the Cnidaria since before the earliest true Bilatera, making these genes pre-Paleozoic.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] It is accepted that the three major animal ANTP-class clusters, Hox, ParaHox, and NK (MetaHox), are the result of segmental duplications.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] A first duplication created MetaHox and ProtoHox, the latter of which later duplicated into Hox and ParaHox.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The clusters themselves were created by tandem duplications of a single ANTP-class homeobox gene.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Gene duplication followed by neofunctionalization is responsible for the many homeobox genes found in eukaryotes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Comparison of homeobox genes and gene clusters has been used to understand the evolution of genome structure and body morphology throughout metazoans.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Hox genes are the most commonly known subset of homeobox genes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] They are essential metazoan genes that determine the identity of embryonic regions along the anterior-posterior axis.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The first vertebrate Hox gene was isolated in *Xenopus* by Edward De Robertis and colleagues in 1984.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The main interest in this set of genes stems from their unique behavior and arrangement in the genome.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Hox genes are typically found in an organized cluster.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The linear order of Hox genes within a cluster is directly correlated to the order in which they are expressed in both time and space during development.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Mutations in these homeotic genes cause displacement of body segments during embryonic development.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] For example, when one gene is lost the segment develops into a more anterior one, while a mutation that leads to a gain of function causes a segment to develop into a more posterior one.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Famous examples are *Antennapedia* and bithorax in *Drosophila*, which can cause the development of legs instead of antennae and the development of a duplicated thorax, respectively.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] In vertebrates, the four paralog clusters are partially redundant in function, but have also acquired several derived functions.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] For example, HoxA and HoxD specify segment identity along the limb axis.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Specific members of the Hox family have been implicated in vascular remodeling, angiogenesis, and disease by orchestrating changes in matrix degradation, integrins, and components of the ECM.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] HoxD3 and HoxB3 are proinvasive, angiogenic genes that upregulate b3 and a5 integrins and Efna1 in ECs, respectively.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] HoxA3 induces endothelial cell (EC) migration by upregulating MMP14 and uPAR.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Conversely, HoxD10 and HoxA5 have the opposite effect of suppressing EC migration and angiogenesis, and stabilizing adherens junctions by upregulating TIMP1/downregulating uPAR and MMP14, and by upregulating Tsp2/downregulating VEGFR2, Efna1, Hif1alpha and COX-2, respectively.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] HoxA5 also upregulates the tumor suppressor p53 and Akt1 by downregulation of PTEN.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Suppression of HoxA5 has been shown to attenuate hemangioma growth.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] HoxA5 has far-reaching effects on gene expression, causing ~300 genes to become upregulated upon its induction in breast cancer cell lines.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] HoxA5 protein transduction domain overexpression prevents inflammation shown by inhibition of TNFalpha-inducible monocyte binding to HUVECs.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] LIM genes (named after the initial letters of the names of three proteins where the characteristic domain was first identified) encode two 60 amino acid cysteine and histidine-rich LIM domains and a homeodomain.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The LIM domains function in protein-protein interactions and can bind zinc molecules.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] LIM domain proteins are found in both the cytosol and the nucleus.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] They function in cytoskeletal remodeling, at focal adhesion sites, as scaffolds for protein complexes, and as transcription factors.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Most Pax genes contain a homeobox and a paired domain that also binds DNA to increase binding specificity, though some Pax genes have lost all or part of the homeobox sequence.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Pax genes function in embryo segmentation, nervous system development, generation of the frontal eye fields, skeletal development, and formation of face structures.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Pax 6 is a master regulator of eye development, such that the gene is necessary for development of the optic vesicle and subsequent eye structures.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Proteins containing a POU region consist of a homeodomain and a separate, structurally homologous POU domain that contains two helix-turn-helix motifs and also binds DNA.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The two domains are linked by a flexible loop that is long enough to stretch around the DNA helix, allowing the two domains to bind on opposite sides of the target DNA, collectively covering an eight-base segment with consensus sequence 5'-ATGCAAAT-3'.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The individual domains of POU proteins bind DNA only weakly, but have strong sequence-specific affinity when linked.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The POU domain itself has significant structural similarity with repressors expressed in bacteriophages, particularly lambda phage.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] As in animals, the plant homeobox genes code for the typical 60 amino acid long DNA-binding homeodomain or in case of the TALE (three amino acid loop extension) homeobox genes for an atypical homeodomain consisting of 63 amino acids.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] According to their conserved intron–exon structure and to unique codomain architectures they have been grouped into 14 distinct classes: HD-ZIP I to IV, BEL, KNOX, PLINC, WOX, PHD, DDT, NDX, LD, SAWADEE and PINTOX.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Conservation of codomains suggests a common eukaryotic ancestry for TALE and non-TALE homeodomain proteins.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] ParaHox genes are analogously found in four areas.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] They include CDX1, CDX2, CDX4; GSX1, GSX2; and PDX1.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Other genes considered Hox-like include EVX1, EVX2; GBX1, GBX2; MEOX1, MEOX2; and MNX1.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] The NK-like (NKL) genes, some of which are considered "MetaHox", are grouped with Hox-like genes into a large ANTP-like group.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Humans have a "distal-less homeobox" family: DLX1, DLX2, DLX3, DLX4, DLX5, and DLX6.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Dlx genes are involved in the development of the nervous system and of limbs.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] They are considered a subset of the NK-like genes.
[src:developmental-biology/homeobox] Human TALE (Three Amino acid Loop Extension) homeobox genes for an "atypical" homeodomain consist of 63 rather than 60 amino acids: IRX1, IRX2, IRX3, IRX4, IRX5, IRX6; MEIS1, MEIS2, MEIS3; MKX; PBX1, PBX2, PBX3, PBX4; PKNOX1, PKNOX2; TGIF1, TGIF2, TGIF2LX, TGIF2LY.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] A **morphogen** is a signaling molecule that contributes to morphogenesis and pattern formation, which are key processes in developmental biology.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Morphogens help organize tissues by creating spatial and temporal differences in signaling activity.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] They are typically defined as signals that generate distinct cellular responses across a population of cells.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] These responses depend on several factors, including signal concentration and the duration of exposure.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] They are also influenced by tissue context and local gene regulatory networks, which affect how cells interpret the signal.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Morphogen distribution can arise through multiple mechanisms.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Diffusion can generate simple, static concentration gradients characteristic of the classical model.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] However, more complex patterns of distribution can also occur.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Mechanisms such as active transport, cytoneme-mediated signaling, extracellular vesicles, and relay signaling contribute to dynamic or spatially complex gradients.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Spatial differences in morphogen signaling interact with feedback loops, tissue mechanics, and gene regulatory networks.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Together, these processes help determine cell fate during development.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Morphogens play a central role in tissue patterning and body plan formation, making them also important in evolutionary developmental biology (evo-devo).
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The term was coined by Alan Turing in the paper "The Chemical Basis of Morphogenesis", where he predicted a chemical mechanism for biological pattern formation, decades before the formation of such patterns was demonstrated.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The concept of the morphogen has a long history in developmental biology, dating back to the work of the pioneering *Drosophila* (fruit fly) geneticist, Thomas Hunt Morgan, in the early 20th century.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Lewis Wolpert refined the morphogen concept in the 1960s with the French flag model, which described how a morphogen could subdivide a tissue into domains of different target gene expression (corresponding to the colours of the French flag).
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] This model was championed by the leading *Drosophila* biologist, Peter Lawrence.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Christiane Nüsslein-Volhard was the first to identify a morphogen, Bicoid, one of the transcription factors present in a gradient in the *Drosophila* syncitial embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] She was awarded the 1995 Nobel Prize in Physiology and Medicine for her work explaining the morphogenic embryology of the common fruit fly.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Groups led by Gary Struhl and Stephen Cohen then demonstrated that a secreted signalling protein, decapentaplegic (the *Drosophila* homologue of transforming growth factor beta), acted as a morphogen during the later stages of *Drosophila* development.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] During early development, morphogen signaling helps organize cell fate by generating differences in gene expression across tissues.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Multiple mechanisms have been proposed to explain how this spatial patterning arises.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Early work focused on the classical model, also known as the French flag model, but later research has expanded this view.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] In classic models, morphogens provide spatial information by forming a concentration gradient that subdivides a field of cells by inducing or maintaining the expression of different target genes at distinct concentration thresholds.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Thus, cells far from the source of the morphogen receive low levels of the signal and express only low-threshold target genes.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] In contrast, cells close to the source receive higher levels and express both low- and high-threshold target genes.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Distinct cell types emerge as a consequence of the different combinations of target gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] In this way, the field of cells is subdivided according to their position relative to the source of the morphogen.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The gradient-based model has traditionally been used to explain how cell type diversity can be generated in embryonic development in animals.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Some of the earliest and best-studied morphogens are transcription factors in early *Drosophila melanogaster* (fruit fly) embryos, where proteins diffuse through a shared cytoplasm before cells fully form.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] However, in most other systems, morphogens are secreted signaling proteins that act between cells through pathways such as Hedgehog, Wnt, BMP, and Nodal.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Although the classical gradient model has been highly influential, many developmental systems use additional or alternative mechanisms.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Morphogen distribution can involve active transport, cytoneme-mediated signaling, extracellular vesicles, or relay signaling between cells.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Cells also interpret signals based on exposure time, feedback loops, gene regulatory networks, and mechanical properties of tissues.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Some of these mechanisms, such as cytoneme-based transport, vesicle-mediated signaling, and the integration of mechanical forces, remain active areas of research.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] There is ongoing debate about how widely they apply and how they interact with classical gradient-based models.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] As a result, current understanding of morphogen signaling reflects a combination of well-established principles and emerging models.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] A morphogen spreads from a localized source and forms a concentration gradient across a developing tissue.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] In developmental biology, 'morphogen' is rigorously used to mean a signalling molecule that acts directly on cells (not through serial induction) to produce specific cellular responses that depend on morphogen concentration.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] This definition concerns the mechanism, not any specific chemical formula, so simple compounds such as retinoic acid (the active metabolite of retinol or vitamin A) may also act as morphogens.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The model is not universally accepted due to specific issues with setting up a gradient in the tissue outlined in the French flag model and subsequent work showing that the morphogen gradient of the Drosophila embryo is more complex than the simple gradient model would indicate.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Proposed mammalian morphogens include retinoic acid, sonic hedgehog (SHH), transforming growth factor beta (TGF-β)/bone morphogenic protein (BMP), and Wnt/beta-catenin.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Morphogens in *Drosophila* include decapentaplegic and hedgehog.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] During development, retinoic acid, a metabolite of vitamin A, is used to stimulate the growth of the posterior end of the organism.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Retinoic acid binds to retinoic acid receptors that act as transcription factors to regulate the expression of Hox genes.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Exposure of embryos to exogenous retinoids, especially in the first trimester, results in birth defects due to deregulation of gene expression.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] TGF-β family members are involved in dorsoventral patterning and the formation of some organs.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Binding of TGF-β to type II TGF beta receptors recruits type I receptors, thereby causing the latter to be transphosphorylated.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The type I receptors activate Smad proteins that in turn act as transcription factors that regulate gene transcription.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Sonic hedgehog (SHH) is a morphogen that are essential to early patterning in the developing embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] SHH binds to the Patched receptor which in the absence of SHH inhibits the Smoothened receptor.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Activated Smoothened in turn causes Gli1, Gli2, and Gli3 to be translocated into the nucleus where they activate target genes such at PTCH1 and Engrailed.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] In most developmental systems, such as human embryos or later *Drosophila* development, syncytia occur only rarely (such as in skeletal muscle), and morphogens are generally secreted signalling proteins.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] These proteins bind to the extracellular domains of transmembrane receptor proteins, which use an elaborate process of signal transduction to communicate the level of morphogen to the nucleus.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The nuclear targets of signal transduction pathways are usually transcription factors, whose activity is regulated in a manner that reflects the level of morphogen received at the cell surface.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Thus, secreted morphogens act to generate gradients of transcription factor activity just like those that are generated in the syncitial *Drosophila* embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Discrete target genes respond to different thresholds of morphogen activity.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The expression of target genes is controlled by segments of DNA called 'enhancers' to which transcription factors bind directly.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] Once bound, the transcription factor then stimulates or inhibits the transcription of the gene and thus controls the level of expression of the gene product (usually a protein).
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] 'Low-threshold' target genes require only low levels of morphogen activity to be regulated and feature enhancers that contain many high-affinity binding sites for the transcription factor.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] 'High-threshold' target genes have relatively fewer binding sites or low-affinity binding sites that require much greater levels of transcription factor activity to be regulated.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The general mechanism by which the morphogen model works, can explain the subdivision of tissues into patterns of distinct cell types, assuming it is possible to create and maintain a gradient.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] However, the morphogen model is often invoked for additional activities such as controlling the growth of the tissue or orienting the polarity of cells within it (for example, the hairs on your forearm point in one direction) which cannot be explained by model.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The organizing role that morphogens play during animal development was acknowledged in the 2014 naming of a new beetle genus, *Morphogenia*.
[src:developmental-biology/morphogen] The type species, *Morphogenia struhli*, was named in honour of Gary Struhl, the US developmental biologist who was instrumental in demonstrating that the *decapentaplegic* and *wingless* genes encode proteins that function as morphogens during *Drosophila* development.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The science of **pattern formation** deals with the visible, (statistically) orderly outcomes of self-organization and the common principles behind similar patterns in nature.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In developmental biology, pattern formation refers to the generation of complex organizations of cell fates in space and time.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The role of genes in pattern formation is an aspect of morphogenesis, the creation of diverse anatomies from similar genes, now being explored in the science of evolutionary developmental biology or evo-devo.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Examples of pattern formation can be found in biology, physics, and other scientific fields, and can readily be simulated with computer graphics, as described in turn below.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Biological patterns such as animal markings, the segmentation of animals, and phyllotaxis are formed in different ways.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In developmental biology, pattern formation describes the mechanism by which initially equivalent cells in a developing tissue in an embryo assume complex forms and functions.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Embryogenesis, such as of the fruit fly *Drosophila*, involves coordinated control of cell fates.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Pattern formation is genetically controlled, and often involves each cell in a field sensing and responding to its position along a morphogen gradient, followed by short-distance cell-to-cell communication through cell-signaling pathways to refine the initial pattern.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In this context, a field of cells is the group of cells whose fates are affected by responding to the same set of positional information cues.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] This conceptual model was first described as the French flag model in the 1960s.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] More generally, the morphology of organisms is patterned by the mechanisms of evolutionary developmental biology, such as changing the timing and positioning of specific developmental events in the embryo.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Cellular automata and neural network models have both been proposed to explain the patterns on some marine mollusc shells such as those of the genus *Conus*.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Bacterial colonies show a large variety of patterns formed during colony growth.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The resulting shapes depend on the growth conditions.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In particular, stresses (hardness of the culture medium, lack of nutrients, etc.) enhance the complexity of the resulting patterns.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Other organisms such as slime moulds display remarkable patterns caused by the dynamics of chemical signaling.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Cellular embodiment (elongation and adhesion) can also have an impact on the developing patterns.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Vegetation patterns such as tiger bush and fir waves form for different reasons.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Tiger bush consists of stripes of bushes on arid slopes in countries such as Niger where plant growth is limited by rainfall.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Each roughly horizontal stripe of vegetation absorbs rainwater from the bare zone immediately above it.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In contrast, fir waves occur in forests on mountain slopes after wind disturbance, during regeneration.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] When trees fall, the trees that they had sheltered become exposed and are in turn more likely to be damaged, so gaps tend to expand downwind.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Meanwhile, on the windward side, young trees grow, protected by the wind shadow of the remaining tall trees.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In flat terrains, additional pattern morphologies appear besides stripes – hexagonal gap patterns and hexagonal spot patterns.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Pattern formation in this case is driven by positive feedback loops between local vegetation growth and water transport towards the growth location.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Pattern formation has been well-studied in chemistry and chemical engineering, including both temperature and concentration patterns.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The Brusselator model developed by Ilya Prigogine and collaborators is one such example that exhibits Turing instability.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Pattern formation in chemical systems often involves oscillatory chemical kinetics or autocatalytic reactions such as the Belousov–Zhabotinsky or Briggs–Rauscher reactions.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In industrial applications such as chemical reactors, pattern formation can lead to temperature hot spots, which can reduce the yield or create hazardous safety problems such as a thermal runaway.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The emergence of pattern formation can be studied by mathematical modeling and simulation of the underlying reaction-diffusion system.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Similarly as in chemical systems, patterns can develop in a weakly ionized plasma of a positive column of a glow discharge.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In such cases, creation and annihilation of charged particles due to collisions of atoms corresponds to reactions in chemical systems.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Corresponding processes are essentially non-linear and lead in a discharge tube to formation of striations with regular or random character.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Other chemical patterns include Liesegang rings.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] When a planar body of fluid under the influence of gravity is heated from below, Rayleigh-Bénard convection can form organized cells in hexagons or other shapes.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] These patterns form on the surface of the Sun and in the mantle of the Earth as well as during more pedestrian processes.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The interaction between rotation, gravity, and convection can cause planetary atmospheres to form patterns, as is seen in Saturn's hexagon and the Great Red Spot and stripes of Jupiter.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] The same processes cause ordered cloud formations on Earth, such as stripes and rolls.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] In the 1980s, Lugiato and Lefever developed a model of light propagation in an optical cavity that results in pattern formation by the exploitation of nonlinear effects.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Precipitating and solidifying materials can crystallize into intricate patterns, such as those seen in snowflakes and dendritic crystals.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Mathematics underlies the other pattern formation mechanisms listed.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Some types of automata have been used to generate organic-looking textures for more realistic shading of 3D objects.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] A popular Photoshop plugin, KPT 6, included a filter called "KPT reaction".
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Reaction produced reaction–diffusion style patterns based on the supplied seed image.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] A similar effect to the KPT reaction can be achieved with convolution functions in digital image processing, with a little patience, by repeatedly sharpening and blurring an image in a graphics editor.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] If other filters are used, such as emboss or edge detection, different types of effects can be achieved.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Computers are often used to simulate the biological, physical, or chemical processes that lead to pattern formation, and they can display the results in a realistic way.
[src:developmental-biology/pattern-formation] Calculations using models like reaction–diffusion or MClone are based on the actual mathematical equations designed by the scientists to model the studied phenomena.
